origin.p:
Notable is also the inclusion in calendar and missal of St Potentinus (June 18), patron saint of Steinfeld Abbey, and St Genebald (September 5), 6th-century bishop of Laon, both associated with the Premonstratensians (
                                    Grotefend (1898)


                                ).

acquisition.p:
It is not known how the manuscript came to the National Library. Drake Boehm and Fajt suggest that it was brought to Sweden by Queen Christina (
                                    Drake Boehm and Fajt

                                ), but this has not been able to be confirmed.  It is listed as No. 19 in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), and as e. 30. 6. 12. in Hammarsköld's catalogue of the 19th century (U 133).

decoNote.p:
: drawing in the Bohemian Beautiful Style  in black ink and red, ocher and brown washes: the Virgin Mary seated with the Christ Child on her lap; standing behind them, a young duke Wenceslaus, armed with sword and shield, girded and dressed in a cloak and mail. All three figures haloed. The name Wenczeslaus in red in top right corner with the outline of a leaf in black and red below. The drawing is dated by Kletzl to the 1370s ( 
    Kletzl

). For further discussion of the decoration, see Lindqvist Sandgren.
